{title: About Horses and Wars}
{artist: Red Steagall}
{composer: unknown}

He nods as rides past the [C]boss
He’s [D7]hummin’ a song that his granddaddy taught him
On the back of that ol’ piebald [G]hoss
And he [C]rides off to cow town when the fall work is over
And goes straight to the Two Minnie’s bar
Where he [D7]dances till morning with the prettiest ladies
And tells ‘em stories about horses and [G]wars
The cow camps are empty the lands full of fences
The cowboys feed hay in a [D7]truck
The chuck wagon stands in a museum in Kansas
Rottin’ and gatherin’ [G]dust
He rocks in an old chair his granddaddy made him
When the plains were still open and [C]free
And his [D7]leggings still hang on a nail by the bed
Gave his spurs to his grandson last [G]spring
Then he rolls him a tight one and stares at the wall
At a picture of him and the [C]boss
For a [D7]while he jumps cattle out of sagebrush and cedar
On the back of that ol’ piebald [G]hoss
Then he [C]dreams he’s in Cowtown a dancin’ till morning
With the girls at the Two Minnie’s bar
Then he [D7]throws down a whiskey with a couple of cowboys
And tells lies about horses and [G]wars

He’s seen in his lifetime a gas-powered jeepney
Then a picture they sent back from [C]mars
But [D7]all that he prays for is to ride off to glory
On the back of that ol’ piebald [G]hoss
While he [C]dreams he’s in Cowtown a dancin’ till morning

With the girls at the Two Minnie’s bar
Then he [D7]throws down a whiskey with a couple of cowboys
And tells lies about horses and [G]wars